BLACK HILLS ENERGY ARKANSAS, INC. OPERATING STATEMENT
UNITED STATES OF AMERICA BEFORE THE FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION Docket No. PR24-___-000
This statement describes how Black Hills Energy Arkansas, Inc. ("Black Hills Energy Arkansas"), a local distribution company, will engage in service arrangements conducted under 18 CFR Section 284.224 for any eligible Shipper. The term "Transporter," as used herein, shall refer to Black Hills Energy Arkansas. Transporter shall be satisfied of Shipper's financial solvency, based on reasonable standards of creditworthiness consistently applied. Transporter shall also be satisfied, in its opinion, that the service will be on behalf of an interstate pipeline or a local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline, and may require appropriate assurance in writing to that effect. Transporter's policy is to render such services on its system only on an interruptible basis. All service will be provided pursuant to written contracts containing terms and conditions generally acceptable to Transporter as set forth herein, and executed after consideration of its existing commitments, the requirements of its local distribution facilities, pipeline design capacity, available pipeline capacity, points of receipt and points of delivery, and other factors deemed material by Transporter. Transporter reserves the right to vary from such general terms provided that any such variations are not materially detrimental to any other shipper similarly situated. 1. DEFINITION OF TERMS. The following terms when used in this Operating Statement shall be construed to have the following meaning, except where the context of their use clearly indicates another meaning: (A) The term "Btu" shall mean British Thermal Unit. (B) The term "Contract" or "Agreement" shall mean the contract pursuant to which Transporter renders service. (C) The term "cubic foot" shall mean the volume of gas which occupies one (1) cubic foot when said gas is at a temperature of sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit, and at a pressure of 14.65 pounds per square inch. (D) The term "day" or "daily" shall mean a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours, beginning and ending as near as practicable to 9:00 a.m. Central Standard or Daylight time. (E) The term "Gas Day Cash Out Index Price" shall mean the Gas Day price survey, mid-point price (for date of physical gas flow) as published by Platts' Gas Daily for the "Spot Prices Delivered to Pipelines" relative to Oklahoma Enable Gas, East. (F) The term "Loan", "Loaned", or "Loaning" shall mean the Transporter's advancement of quantities of gas to Shipper from the Transporter's system assets at a Loan Point pursuant to a Market Center Services Agreement.
(G) The term "Loan Point" shall mean a nomination point determined by the Transporter at which quantities may be Loaned pursuant to a Market Center Services Agreement. (H) The term "Market Center Services" or "MCS" shall mean interruptible Parking, Loaning, Wheeling, or Title Tracking Transfer services provided in accordance with this Operating Statement and subject to a Master Market Center Services Agreement. (I) The term "Master Market Center Services Agreement" shall mean the Agreement between Shipper and Transporter pursuant to which Transporter provides Market Center Services to Shipper. (J) The term "Mcf" shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas. (K) The term "MMBtu" shall mean one million (1,000,000) Btu's. (L) The term "month" or "monthly" shall mean the period beginning at or as near as practicable to 9:00 a.m., Central Standard or Daylight time, on the first day of the calendar month and ending as near as practicable to 9:00 a.m. on the first day of the next succeeding calendar month. (M) The term "Park", "Parking", or "Parked" shall mean acceptance by the Transporter of quantities of gas tendered by the Shipper at a Park Point pursuant to a Master Market Center Services Agreement. (N) The term "Park Point" shall mean a nomination point determined by the Transporter at which quantities may be parked pursuant to a Master Market Center Services Agreement. (O) The term "Shipper" shall mean the party so identified in the Contract, or its designee. (P) The term "Title Tracking Transfer" or "TTT" shall mean service provided in accordance with this Operating Statement that consists of the transfer of Parked or Loaned quantities between Shippers who have executed Master Market Center Services Agreements from one Shipper's MCS account to another Shipper's MCS account, prior to the time the quantities are Unparked or redelivered. (Q) The term "Transaction Request" shall mean an exhibit to the Master Market Center Services Agreement for each individual Parking, Loaning, Wheeling, or TTT action. (R) The term "transportation service" shall mean the performance of transportation on Transporter's transmission and/or gathering systems. (S) The term "Transporter" shall mean the party so identified in the Contract, or its designee.
(T) The term "Unpark" shall mean the delivery of gas from a Shipper's Parking account to an Agreement of Shipper or to an Agreement of another Shipper. (U) The term "Wheeling" shall mean service provided in accordance with this Operating Statement that allows the Unparked or Loan redelivery quantity to occur at a system location other than the original Park Point or Loan Point, by exchange or displacement and subject to operational flexibility, as detailed in the Transaction Request. (V) The term "year" shall mean a period of three hundred sixty-five (365) consecutive days beginning on the Starting Date specified in the Contract for the commencement of the term of service or any anniversary thereof; provided, however, that any year which contains a date of February 29, shall consist of three hundred sixty-six (366) consecutive days. 2. SERVICES. (A) Services Offered. Subject to Transporter's determination that it has available capacity, Transporter will offer the following services to Shippers, as described in this Section: interruptible transportation service as described in paragraph 2(B) of this Operating Statement, and Market Center Services as described in paragraph 2(C) of this Operating Statement. All such services shall be recorded and accounted for on a daily basis. Services hereunder shall be interruptible in nature and subordinate to any and all firm services supplied by Transporter's intrastate natural gas distribution utility operations, including the management of Transporter's system to support its intrastate firm sales and transportation services. In the event that interruptible service has already commenced and Transporter learns that the continued furnishing of interruptible service may prevent Transporter from meeting all of its service obligations hereunder or as an intrastate natural gas distribution utility, then Transporter may, at its discretion and upon giving at least one hours prior notice to Shipper, interrupt the continuation of any or all of the interruptible Services hereunder. A Shipper's right to interruptible services shall not extend beyond the term of any Agreement between Shipper and Transporter unless both Transporter and Shipper expressly extend the term of such Agreement in writing. Further, Shipper's rights to services maybe limited to the use of specific receipt and delivery points. Shipper shall be responsible for arranging all upstream (or downstream) interstate pipeline transportation services necessary or attendant to the provision of interruptible services hereunder.
(B) Interruptible Transportation Service.
Consistent with the provisions hereof and any terms of service reflected in an Agreement between Shipper and Transporter, Shipper may engage Transporter to transport gas hereunder, on an interruptible basis, from any designated receipt point to any designated delivery point. All transportation gas received by Transporter shall be accounted for on a daily basis. (C) Interruptible Market Center Services. Consistent with the provisions hereof and any terms of service reflected in an Agreement between Shipper and Transporter, Shipper may engage Transporter to provide Parking service, Loaning service, Wheeling service, and/or TTT service. Parking, Loaning, and Wheeling services are subject to interruption at any time and such interruptions may be in effect for extended periods of time. The Master Market Center Services Agreement shall state a total quantity that may be Parked or Loaned at any one time under the sum total of all Transaction Requests. A Transaction Request shall be executed for each request for Market Center Services and shall state the term of the request and a maximum and minimum daily gas quantity associated with the request. Service rendered under a Transaction Request shall be provided for a minimum one (1) day term. Shipper shall not redeliver more than the quantity Loaned and shall not Unpark more than the quantity Parked under the Transaction Request. In the event Shipper fails to adhere to any terms in the Transaction Request, Shipper shall be charged up to the maximum allowable rate for the service and quantity outside the parameters of the Transaction Request. (1) Parking service. Parking service shall consist of (1) the receipt of gas by Transporter (when nominated by Shipper) at a Park Point, and the holding of the Parked quantity for Shipper's account for a specified period of time, and (2) the Unparking (when nominated by Shipper) of the Parked quantities to Shipper by Transporter at the original Park Point. Requests to Unpark Parked quantities at a different point shall be treated as Wheeling and must be agreed to simultaneously with the Park transaction. In the event that Parked quantities have not been returned to Shipper at the termination date of the Transaction Request, and no mutually agreed extension to the Transaction Request occurs, the Parked quantity shall become property of Transporter at no cost to Transporter, free and clear of any and all adverse claims. (2) Loaning service. Loaning service shall consist of (1) the advancement of gas by Transporter (when nominated by Shipper) at a Loan Point, for Shipper's account for a specified period of time and (2) the Loan payback (when nominated by Shipper) of the Loan quantity to Transporter by Shipper at the original Loan Point. Requests to redeliver Loaned quantities at a different point shall be treated as Wheeling and must be agreed to simultaneously with the Loan transaction.
In the event that Loan quantities have not been returned to Transporter at the termination date of the Transaction Request, and no mutually agreed extension to the Transaction Request occurs, the Loan quantity shall be cashed out at the highest of the following: (1) the Gas Day Cash Out Index Price on the Gas Day the Loan occurred; (2) the Gas Day Cash Out Index Price on the termination date of the Transaction Request; (3) the Gas Day Cash Out Index Price on the Gas Day Transporter made replacement purchases for the Loan amount; (4) the average Gas Day Cash Out Index Price for the month in which the Loan occurred; or (5) the average Gas Day Cash Out Index Price for the month in which the Transaction Request terminated. (3) Wheeling service. Wheeling service shall allow the Unparked or Loan redelivery quantity to occur at a system location other than the original Park Point or Loan Point, by exchange or displacement and subject to operational flexibility, as detailed in the Transaction Request. Wheeling service must be agreed to at the time of the initial request. Any later request to use a system location other than the original Park Point or Loan Point shall be considered transportation service and must be accomplished by nomination and scheduling. (4) TTT service. TTT service shall consist of the transfer of Parked or Loaned quantities between Shippers from one Shipper's Transaction Request account to another Shipper's Transaction Request account, prior to the time the quantities are Unparked or Redelivered.
(D) Authorization and Scheduling of Interruptible Services. All requests to schedule interruptible services, subject to limits imposed by Transporter to limit such services and Transporter's right to refuse to schedule any discounted interruptible volumes, shall be authorized on a non-discriminatory basis in order of the highest rates (at or below the maximum rates established hereunder) agreed to be paid for such service. In the event of any ties with respect to the rates agreed to be paid for such service, and in the case where Transporter is unable to provide all of the service requested at such rates, then volumes shall be scheduled on the basis of the date and time of receipt by Transporter of the interruptible request form, as determined by Transporter. All service authorizations hereunder shall be granted solely on the condition that Transporter has determined that it has adequate capacity to provide Shipper the service requested. Market Center Services shall be the last quantities scheduled on the system and shall be scheduled in priority by total revenue over the term of the Transaction Request.
(E) Eligibility.
Shipper shall be eligible for services hereunder upon satisfying all the terms and conditions specified herein as well as the terms and conditions set forth in any Agreement between Shipper and Transporter for services hereunder.
(F) Requests for Service. All requests to schedule services hereunder may be made verbally on an initial basis, but must be reduced to writing (utilizing forms specified by Transporter) and delivered to Transporter prior to the scheduled flow of gas requested therein. This requirement may be satisfied by direct telephone facsimile transmission by a Shipper to Transporter of an appropriate nomination/scheduling form, signed by an authorized representative of Shipper and setting forth the details of any service request or nomination. Transporter may require daily service nominations or changes in daily service nominations from Shipper via telephone facsimile transmission of a form provided for that purpose. No such daily service nominations or changes in daily service nominations may exceed the overall maximum service limits prescribed by this Operating Statement or the terms of any Agreement between Shipper and Transporter related to services hereunder. Transporter reserves the right, upon notice to Shipper, to record any or all telephone calls relating to requests for service and to utilize such recordings to resolve any disputes arising from Shipper's requests for service. Requests for service shall be made directly to Transporter or to its duly authorized agent. All requests for service must be received by Transporter or its agent in sufficient time to allow Transporter to finalize its nominations and confirmations in compliance with the advance notice requirements of any transporting interstate natural gas pipeline being relied upon to move gas to Transporter's facilities. Each request for services shall provide all information required by Transporter, including: (1) the rates agreed upon for the services to be provided; (2) the maximum daily quantity or quantities to be transported, Parked, Loaned, Wheeled, or transferred; (3) the day and dates when such service is expected to commence and to terminate; (4) the point(s) at which Transporter is expected to receive and/or make deliveries of such gas, and (5) any other information required by Transporter. (G) Processing of Service Requests. Transporter shall verbally respond to each request to schedule service hereunder, either (1) that Shipper is authorized to commence the service(s) requested, or (2) that Transporter cannot provide such service(s). Transporter, or its duly authorized agent, shall use reasonable best efforts to respond verbally to all such service requests as soon as possible, and shall follow such response with written confirmation either by telephone, email, facsimile transmission, or by U.S. Mail.
Nothing contained herein shall be construed to mean that any services other than those established pursuant to the terns of any Agreement between Shipper and Transporter shall be provided to Shipper, or that Transporter has any obligation to provide services under any conditions which, in Transporter's discretion, may
jeopardize Transporter's ability to render adequate and reliable services to its intrastate natural gas sales and transportation customers. Once a transaction is scheduled and confirmed hereunder, Transporter agrees to supply such service subject to the terms hereof, any operational flow orders or curtailment of any upstream pipeline serving Transporter's facilities, or other similar event, which might reasonably prevent Transporter from furnishing such service.
3. FACILITIES. Transporter shall not be obligated to construct, add, alter or modify any facilities to receive and/or deliver gas, or to provide any of the services hereunder. 4. BILLING AND PAYMENT. Shipper agrees to furnish, or cause to be furnished, if required, to Transporter on or before the tenth (10th) day of each month a statement allocating the quantities of gas delivered to Transporter during the preceding month at each receipt point hereunder among the various interest in the wells from which gas is being delivered under the Agreement and all other parties or interests delivering gas to Transporter at said point; and Transporter shall be entitled to rely conclusively on said statement. Notwithstanding the ongoing provisions, Transporter shall have the right to bill Shipper each month hereunder on the basis of nominated quantities or estimated quantities, provided that adjustment shall be made to such quantities in subsequent months billings based on actual quantities delivered. Transporter's bills will be rendered promptly after the close of each billing period and shall be paid to Transporter within twenty-two (22) days after the date rendered. Amounts past due hereunder shall bear interest from the due date until paid at the maximum lawful rate but not more than the rate of interest effective from time to time under 18.C.F.R. Section 154.501. Upon default of payment for a period in excess of thirty (30) days after payment is due, Transporter upon ten (10) days' written notice to Shipper may suspend receipt and delivery of gas until satisfactory credit arrangements have been made. Transporter thereafter, may require as a condition of re-commencement or continuation of service a guaranty, deposit; bond or letter of credit or increase in an existing guaranty, deposit, bond, or letter of credit at any time to secure payment of bills in a total amount that does not exceed the amount provided in Section 16 of this Operating Statement. 5. NOTICE. Any notice, request, demand, statement or bill provided for herein and in the Contract, and any other notice which either Transporter or Shipper may desire to give to the other, shall be in writing and if delivered shall be considered as duly delivered when mailed by registered or certified mail to the Post Office address of Transporter or Shipper as indicated in the Contract or at such other address as either shall designate by formal written notice to the other. Routine communications, including monthly statements and payments if received, shall be considered as duly delivered when mailed by registered, certified or ordinary mail.
6. GOVERNMENTAL REGULATIONS. This contract shall be subject to all relevant present and future local, state and federal laws and all rules, regulations and orders of regulatory authorities having jurisdiction over either or both parties including, but not limited to, 18 CFR Section 284.224, and the obligations of both parties hereunder are subject to obtaining whatever regulatory approvals and authorizations are necessary for the
lawful implementation of any Agreement on continuing conditions satisfactory to the party affected. Neither party shall be held in default for failure to perform hereunder if such failure is due to good faith compliance with the requirements of any such laws, orders, rules and regulations. Should such governmental regulations or orders reduce the rates for the services provided in the Agreement, such rates shall be reduced only by the difference between the total amount of money due each month under the terms and conditions of the Agreement, and the total amount of money permitted to be charged during such month under any applicable regulations and orders. Shipper shall cooperate with Transporter by providing promptly all information and in making whatever reports or filings are necessary in regard to service rendered under the Agreement.
7. MEASUREMENT. Except as may be otherwise provided elsewhere herein or required by law, the measurement and testing of gas received and delivered hereunder shall be done by Transporter, or its designee, as measuring party in accordance with the following: (A) The unit of volume shall be 1,000 cubic feet of gas (Mcf) at a temperature base of 60 degrees Fahrenheit and at a pressure base of 14.65 pounds per square inch absolute. Whenever the actual conditions of pressure and temperature of the particular gas stream being measured differ from the above standard, conversion of the volume from such actual conditions to the above standard conditions shall be made in accordance with the Ideal Gas Laws corrected for super-compressibility in accordance with the method customarily used by the measuring party. The measuring party may use any applicable findings and field rules of regulatory authorities with jurisdiction for purposes of computations hereunder. (B) Measurements of gas shall always be in accordance with requirements of law, and if the procedures, bases, or standards herein contemplated to be used in the determination of gas volumes are changed by law or regulatory action, the applicable rates shall be appropriately modified and adjusted to the extent necessary to the end that calculates to determine sums of money due hereunder after the change will reach the same end result in dollars and cents as would have been reached in the absence of such change. (C) The temperature of the gas at each relevant point shall be (i) determined by a recording thermometer, (ii) determined by taking the average of the daily readings of an indicating thermometer, or (iii) assumed by mutual agreement to be 60 degrees Fahrenheit; provided that, if a recording thermometer is not being used, Shipper shall have the right, by reimbursing the cost of the equipment and its installation, to require the use of a recording thermometer. The Btu content of the gas per cubic foot shall be determined on a dry basis in accordance with good engineering practice in a manner reasonably calculated to result in a fair and accurate determination. (D) The specific gravity of the gas shall be determined in accordance with good engineering practice as often as found necessary in operation.
(E) Standard type measuring and testing equipment necessary to measure and determine quantities hereunder shall be installed, operated and maintained in a workmanlike manner. Readings, calibrations, tests, repairs and adjustments of said equipment, and changing of charts, shall be done only by employees or agents of measuring party and in accordance with good engineering practice as often as necessary in operation. Orifice meters, if used, shall be installed and operated, and volumes computed, in accordance with the most current edition of the American Gas Association Measurement Committee Report No. 3 and Appendices thereto, and such amendments thereof as measuring party may place in use on its system for transactions of this type. Shipper shall have access to the measuring and testing equipment at reasonable times, and shall have the right to have a representative present at tests, calibrations and adjustments thereof. Upon request by Shipper for a special test of any meter or auxiliary equipment, the accuracy of same shall be verified promptly, provided that the cost of such special test shall be borne by Shipper unless the percentage of inaccuracy is found to be more than two percent (2%). If upon any test the total inaccuracy resulting from meter errors and errors in auxiliary equipment, including any recording calorimeters, exceeds two percent (2%), then previous readings shall be corrected to zero error for the period, but not beyond the close of the preceding accounting month; if said total inaccuracy is not more than two percent (2%), the previous reading shall be considered correct but the equipment shall be adjusted to read correctly. Measuring party shall not be required to verify the accuracy of such equipment more than once in any 90-day period.
(F) If any meter or auxiliary equipment is out of service or out for repair for a period of time so that the quantify of gas delivered cannot be ascertained or computed from the reading thereof, then the quantity delivered during such period shall be estimated upon the basis of the best data available, using the first of the following methods which is feasible: (i) by correcting the error of the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test, or mathematical calculations; (ii) by using the registration of any check equipment installed and accurately registering, or (iii) by estimating the volume on the basis of deliveries during preceding periods under similar conditions when the equipment was registering accurately. (G) Upon request, measurement charts and records shall be submitted to Shipper for examination, the same to be returned within twenty (20) days. The measurement charts and records for a given accounting month shall be conclusively presumed correct if no written objection thereto is served on Transporter within the 12-month period following the given accounting month. All test data, meter charts and similar records shall be preserved for a period of at least one year. (H) The measurement and testing of gas for purposes of the Agreement shall only be by the equipment operated by measuring party, but Shipper may install, operate and maintain, at Shipper's own cost, risk and expense and in the same manner as is required for the primary equipment hereunder, check measuring and testing equipment of standard type, provided that the same does not interfere with the operation of the primary equipment. Transporter shall have the same rights with respect to check equipment as Shipper has with respect to the primary equipment.
(I) If Transporter causes any or all of the foregoing measurement and testing procedures to be done by a third-party designee, then in such event:
(1) Shipper's rights hereunder with respect to the third-party's equipment and procedures will be subject to reasonable arrangements made by Transporter with such third party. (2) If the third party's usual and customary procedures differ in particular respects from the detailed procedures set out above, then the third-party's procedures and measured quantities resulting therefrom shall be acceptable and used hereunder so long as they are consistent with good engineering practice in the industry. 8. FORCE MAJEURE. Neither Shipper nor Transporter shall be liable to the other for failure to perform their respective obligations under any Agreement due to acts or conditions beyond the reasonable control of the parties affected. The obligations of the affected party to perform shall be suspended so long as and to the extent that performance is prevented by the occurrence of such acts or conditions. Such acts or conditions shall be deemed to include, but not be limited to, fire, labor disputes, acts of God, the elements, wars, epidemics, riots, civil disturbances, explosions, breakdown of equipment, tests and repairs of pipeline facilities, freezing of wells or pipelines, temporary failure of gas supply, requirements of local, state or federal authorities, inability of any intermediate gatherers or transporters of the gas necessary to the performance of the service by Transporter to gather or transport the gas due to force majeure, failure of appropriate regulatory approvals or lack of sufficient capacity, the inability of Transporter to obtain or maintain such regulatory authorizations as may be necessary for the lawful performance of the service contemplated hereby on continuing conditions satisfactory to Transporter, the curtailment of service by Transporter in accordance with Transporter's curtailment plan as effective from time to time, and any other cause similar or dissimilar, not within the reasonable control of the party claiming relief. The party affected shall notify the other promptly and shall remedy the cause of suspension with reasonable diligence, retaining to such party unqualified discretion in settling labor disputes. 9. OPERATING INFORMATION AND FORECASTS. Shipper, upon request, shall furnish Transporter from time to time such reasonable data, including schedules of expected tenders and requests for deliveries, as in Transporter's judgement are necessary for the proper analysis of the daily and annual gas load requirements of Shipper at each of the delivery and redelivery points. Shipper at all times shall keep Transporter informed of anticipated significant changes in the size and character of such load requirements. 10. RECEIPT OF GAS FOR SERVICES. (A) The Shipper must tender the gas for services hereunder at a mutually agreeable point or points on Transporter's system at whatever pressure is necessary to effect deliveries of the gas against the fluctuating working pressure maintained in Transporter's system at that point from time to time, up to 500 psig. Transporter
will not be obligated to accept any gas into its system that does not meet the following specifications:
(1) Water. The gas shall in no event have a water content in excess of seven (7) pounds of water per, million (1,000,000) cubic feet of gas measured at a pressure base of fourteen and seven-tenths (14.7) pound per square inch absolute and at a temperature of sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit, as determined by a method generally acceptable for use in the gas industry. (2) Hydrogen Sulphide. The gas shall not contain more, than one-fourth (1/4) grain of hydrogen sulphide per-hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative test after the presence of hydrogen sulphide has been indicated by qualitative test, which shall consist of exposing a strip of white filter paper, recently moistened with a solution of one hundred (100) grains of lead acetate in one hundred (100) cubic centimeters of water, to the gas for one and one-half (1 1/2) minutes in an apparatus previously purged, through which the gas is flowing at the rate of approximately five (5) cubic feet per hour, the gas from the jet not impinging upon the test paper, and which qualitative test shall be deemed to be satisfied, if, after this exposure, the test paper is found not distinctly darker than a second paper freshly moistened with a similar solution not exposed to the gas. (3) Total Sulphur. The gas shall not contain more than five (5) grains of total sulphur per one hundred (100) cubic feet of gas. (4) Temperatures. The gas shall not have a temperature of less than forty (40) degrees Fahrenheit; nor more than one hundred twenty (120) degrees Fahrenheit. (5) Carbon Dioxide. The gas shall not contain in excess of two percent (2%) by volume of carbon dioxide. (6) Oxygen. The gas shall not contain in excess of two tenths of one percent (0.2 of 1%) by volume of oxygen.
(7) Nitrogen. The gas shall not contain in excess of three percent (3%) by volume of nitrogen.
(8) Natural Gasoline. The gas, shall not have in excess of two-tenths (0.2) gallon per thousand (1,000) cubic feet of those certain liquefiable hydrocarbons commonly referred to as natural gasoline, as determined by the charcoal absorption method as prescribed by the American Gas Association in its testing Code No. 101, effective January 1, 1943.
(9) Objectionable Liquids and Solids and Dilution. The gas shall (i) be in its natural state as produced from wells, (ii) be free of objectionable liquids and solids, (iii) be commercially free from dust, gums, gum forming
constituents, or other liquid or solid matter which might become separated from the gas in the course of transportation through pipelines, and (iv) not be subjected, to any treatment or process which will change the chemical composition of any of the component parts of such gas, permit or cause the admission of oxygen or which will dilute such gas or otherwise cause it to fail to meet the quality specifications described herein.
(10) Heating Value. (i) Maximum. The gas shall not have a heating value in excess of 1,100 total British Thermal Units per cubic foot. (ii) Minimum. The gas shall not have a heating value of less than 975 total British Thermal Units per cubic foot. (B) Transporter will be responsible for installing and operating the necessary tap and measurement facilities on its system to receive and measure the gas tendered by Shipper hereunder. 11. DELIVERY OF GAS BY TRANSPORTER. (A) Except as may be otherwise specified, the gas shall be tendered for delivery by Transporter and received by Shipper at the working pressures maintained at the designated point of delivery, from time to time up to 500 psig. It is recognized that the gas delivered to Shipper by Transporter will not be the same gas that Transporter received from Shipper. Except as may be provided with respect to any given delivery point, the gas delivered will meet the quality specifications applicable to gas that Transporter received hereunder as provided in paragraph 10(A) of this Operating Statement. Transporter will use its best efforts consistent with the prudent operation of its pipeline system to deliver gas meeting such specifications but shall not be liable in damages for failure to do so, unless caused by the negligence or willful misconduct of Transporter. If the gas tendered by Transporter fails at any time to conform to any of said specifications, then Shipper shall notify Transporter of such deficiency and thereupon may, at Shipper's option, refuse to accept delivery without liability, pending correction by Transporter. Shipper will not be obligated to receive gas tendered for delivery which does not meet the foregoing specifications and may terminate this contract if Transporter does not bring the gas up to specification within a reasonable time after written notice that it is below specifications.
(B) The point where responsibility for the gas shall pass to Shipper shall be at the outlet of Transporter's facilities at the designated point of delivery. Shipper shall provide reasonable access to the premises at the point of delivery for any purpose connected with this service.
(C) Transporter shall install, operate and maintain at Shipper's expense whatever facilities are necessary to deliver the gas at the point or points of delivery hereunder
and shall indemnify Shipper and hold it harmless from and against any and all claims, actions, suits, damages, liabilities, penalties, costs and expenses arising out of use, possession or presence of the gas before it passes the point of delivery. (D) Shipper shall install, operate and maintain at its own expenses whatever facilities are necessary to safely receive and utilize the gas at and beyond the point of delivery hereunder, and shall indemnify Transporter and hold it harmless from and against any and all claims, actions, suits, damages, liabilities, penalties, costs and expenses arising out of the use, possession, or presence of the gas at and after it passes the point of delivery.
12. WARRANTY OF TITLE. Each party warrants the title to or the full right to deliver all gas delivered, or caused to be delivered, by it to the other party. Shipper further represents and warrants that it will pay and satisfy, or make provisions for the payment and satisfaction of, any taxes and all claims of every nature whatsoever in, to, or in respect of gas delivered by it; and Shipper hereby agrees to defend at its cost, and, when notified by Transporter, to indemnify, and defend if requested by Transporter, Transporter against all suits, judgments, claims, demands, causes of action, costs, losses, and expenses, including reasonable attorney's fees, arising out of or in any way connected with any claims to the gas delivered to Transporter. Transporter assumes no obligation whatever to any royalty owner or to the owner of any other interest of any kind in any gas delivered at the Point(s) of Receipt, and Shipper or its seller shall pay all such royalties or other interests upon or in respect to such gas.
13. ASSIGNMENT. Any Agreement shall not be assigned by Shipper in whole or in part, nor shall Shipper agree to provide services to others by use of any capacity contracted for under the Agreement, without Transporter's prior written consent. In addition to all other rights and remedies, Transporter may terminate the Agreement immediately if it is assigned by Shipper or if Shipper subcontracts the capacity to others without such prior consent, whether the assignment or contract be voluntary or by operation of law or otherwise subject to the above, the respective rights and obligations of the parties under the Agreement shall extend to and be binding upon their heirs, successors, assigns and legal representatives.
14. MINIMUM QUANTITY.
